The Baeyer–Drewson indigo synthesis (1882) is an organic reaction in which indigo is prepared from 2-nitrobenzaldehyde and acetone [1][2] 
The reaction is classified as an aldol condensation. As a practical route to indigo, this method was displaced by routes from aniline.[3] 
Mechanism 
Note 
In the English literature this reaction is usually called Baeyer–Drewson reaction, although the author of the original paper was called Drewsen. 
References 
The Baeyer–Emmerling indole synthesis is a method for synthesizing indole from a (substituted) ortho-nitrocinnamic acid and iron powder in strongly basic solution.[1][2] This reaction was discovered by Adolf von Baeyer and Adolph Emmerling in 1869.[3] [4] 
Reaction mechanism 
The reaction of iron powder with o-nitrocinnamic acid reduces the nitro group to a nitroso. 
The nitrogen then condenses with a carbon on the alkene chain with loss of a molecule of water to form a ring. 
Decarboxylation gives indole. 
