Allotopes are regions on an antibody which have non-varying structures. 
Contrast this with idiotopes which have varying structure from one antibody type to another. 
Anti-histone antibodies are autoantibodies that are found in 50%-70% of patients with systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) and in more than 95% of patients with drug-induced lupus erythematosus.[1] 
An ELISA for detecting anti-histone antibodies is said to be positive when there is more than 25 units/ml anti-histone antibodies in a blood sample.[2] 
