Felicia Adetowun Omolara Ogunsheye (née Banjo; born 5 December 1926) is the first female professor in Nigeria. 
She was a professor of library and information science at the University of Ibadan.[1][2] 
Early life and education 
Ogunsheye was born on December 5, 1926 in Benin City, Nigeria, to parents from Ogun State.[3] She is the elder sister of Lieutenant Colonel Victor Banjo and Ademola Banjo. 
She had her secondary education at Queens College, before becoming the only female student at Yaba College of Technology in 1946. 
In 1948, she received her diploma, becoming the first woman to graduate from the school.[4] She attended University College Ibadan, then went on to Newnham College, Cambridge University, UK, to study Geography on scholarship, earning BA and MA degrees in 1952 and 1956, respectively; she became the first Nigerian woman there.[3] She earned another master's degree in Library Science from Simmons College, Massachusetts, USA in 1962.[5] 
She established the Abadina Media Resource Centre Library of the University of Ibadan.[1] In 1973, she became a professor at University of Ibadan. 
Between 1977 and 1979, she was appointed as the dean of faculty of education at the same university. 
She was the first woman to become a dean in any Nigerian university.[2] She served as a consultant to various organisations including the International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions (lFLA); UNESCO; International Association of School Librarianship (IASL); the International Federation of Documentalists (FID); the British Council and the World Bank. 
Adetola Juyitan is a Nigerian social entrepreneur, Chief Executive Officer of Glitz Group of companies[1] and 2019 President of Junior Chamber International Nigeria.[2][3] 
Life 
Juyitan, originally from Ondo State but was born in Lagos as the first of five children. 
She graduated with a Bachelor's degree in Accounting from Ekiti State University and obtained her Master of Business Administration from Lincoln University, California, USA.[4] 
In 2004, She started her career at Zenith Bank Plc as a Youth Corper then rose in rank until September 2013 when she joined United Bank for Africa as Business Manager[5] and then left in 2015 to establish her own company called Glitz Occasions Nigeria Limited.[6][7] 
She was elected as the National President of Junior Chamber International Nigeria in 2019.[8][9] 
