Personal life 
Samantha Biffot (born 1985) is a Gabonese-French screenwriter, film producer and film director. 
External links 
Biography 
Biffot was born in Paris in 1985. 
She spent her childhood between Gabon, South Korea and France, and her multicultural upbringing influenced her later filmmaking.[1] After receiving her baccalaureate, she studied at the École Supérieure de Réalisation Audiovisuelle in Paris where she obtained a degree in cinema in 2007. 
Upon graduation, Biffot completed several television and film internships in France. 
Biffot returned to Gabon in 2010 where she established the production company "Princesse M Production" with Pierre-Adrien Ceccaldi. 
In 2011, she organized workshops in screenplay, production, image and editing as part of the International Festival of School Courts in Libreville.[2] 
In 2013, her TV series L'Œil de la cité (The Eye of the city) received the prize for the best African series at the Panafrican Film and Television Festival of Ouagadougou.[3] The series examined ritual crimes and environmental and social problems, with each episode having a moral at the end. 
She said she was influenced by the American series Tales from the Crypt, and her series was produced by the Institut Gabonais de l'Image et du Son.[4] In 2016, Biffot released the documentary The African Who Wanted to Fly, depicting the life of Gabonese kung fu master Luc Bendza. 
The film received the Special Jury Prize at the Festival Escales Socumentaires de Libreville as well as being named Best Documentary Film at the 2017 Burundi International Film and Audiovisual Festival.[5] The African Who Wanted to Fly was also screened at the Internationales Dokumentarfilmfestival München and the African Film Festival in New York.[6] 
Filmography 
References 
Angela Aquereburu (born 11 January 1977) is a Togolese screenwriter, film producer and film director. 
External links 
Biography 
Aquereburu was born in Togo to a mother from Guadeloupe. 
Interested in the arts from a young age, she was educated in Togo and Pointe-a-Pitre, Guadeloupe before moving to Paris to study at ESCP Business School.[1] She earned a master's degree in entrepreneurship.[2] Aquereburu married actor Jean-Luc Rabatel and worked in human resources for several years. 
In 2008, while vacationing in Togo, she realized that there were only soap operas on television, and together with her husband came up with the idea for a series about motorcycle taxis.[1] The following year, Aquereburu and Rabatel moved to Lomé and founded the audiovisual production company Yobo Studios.[3] Their idea of a taxi show formed the basis for Zem, a mini-series of 26 five-minute episodes, co-produced by Canal + Afrique.[1] 
Her next project was the short series Palabres.[2] In 2017, she launched Hospital IT, which tackles societal problems like malaria and skin whitening and focuses on the characters Idriss and Tania. 
Aquereburu said she was inspired by her second pregnancy to create the show. Grey's Anatomy served as a major influence.[2] It won the prize for best series at the Vues d'Afrique Festival in Montreal.[2] 
In 2018, Aquereburu served as the presenter for Les Maternelles d'Afrique, an African version of the French show La Maison des Maternelles. She was inspired by the concerns of African mothers as well as her own family. 
The show tackles the conroversial subject of polygamy in an impartial manner.[4] 
Filmography 
