Ngardy Conteh George (born c. 1979) is a Sierra Leonean-Canadian film director and editor. 
External links 
Biography 
The youngest of four siblings, George was born in Freetown but moved to Canada in her childhood. 
She attended the University of New Orleans on a track and field scholarship.[1] After graduation, she turned her focus towards film production and telling the stories of the African diaspora.[2] In 2004, she directed her first film, Soldiers for the Streets, detailing Ras King's efforts to educate and empower youth.[3] She directed the documentary series Literature Alive in 2005, featuring Caribbean-Canadian authors. 
In addition to directing, George has served as a video editor for I Want to Be a Desi 2, (documentary short, Dir. Allan Tong), Something Beautiful, Arts & Minds for Bravo!, Food & Drink TV and The Marilyn Denis Show for CTV.[2] With her company Mattru Media, she produced The Rhyming Chef Barbuda, a cooking show featuring hip-hop filmed in the Caribbean, and two seasons of the hip-hop show Cypher.[4] 
In 2008, with help from Concerned Citizens and Friends of Sierra Leone, she directed the documentary The Circle of Slavery that explored the historical ties between Sierra Leone and Canada.[1] In 2014, George directed the sports documentary The Flying Stars, supported by the Sundance Documentary Film Fund. 
It was named Best documentary at the 2015 BronzeLens Film Festival.[5] 
