Souhir Ben Amara (born 27 November 1985) is a Tunisian actress. 
Television 
References 
External links 
Biography 
Her career began on television with the Maktoub and Choufli Hal series in 2008. 
She starred as Maliha in Min Ayam Mliha in 2010. 
Ben Amara made her film debut in Always Brando (2011), directed by Ridha Béhi. 
She played the symbolic role of Zena and was cast last minute when the director did not like the actress chosen for the role.[1] In 2012, Ben Amara played Aicha in Millefeuille, directed by Nouri Bouzid, dealing with issues with the hijab.[2] 
In 2013, she played the role of Donia in the miniseries Yawmiyat Imraa.[3] In 2019, Ben Amara starred in the historical soap opera Kingdoms of Fire.[4] She had a principal role in Sortilège (2019), directed by Ala Eddine Slim.[5] She was attracted by its script, and her character meets the soldier after moving from a forest. The film premiered at the Cannes Film Festival, and she called the film the cinema of perception.[6] 
Ben Amara supported the Arab Spring and participated in the events, but feels bitter that politicians stole the popular will.[7] She is opposed to the legalization of cannabis but supports reducing the penalties associated with it. She has said that her ideal role would be that of a tomboy character.[2] 
