Mariama Sylla Faye is a Senegalese film director, actress, and singer. 
Biography 
Sylla was born in Dakar and is the younger sister of the writer and filmmaker Khady Sylla.[1][2] Her mother worked in the cinema office, and Sylla became passionate about cinema at the age of seven, as many films were screened in the family courtyard.[3] In 1996 she received her diploma at the École supérieure d'art dramatique de Genève. 
Sylla began her career as a theatre actress in French-speaking Switzerland. 
She performed under the directors Claude Stratz, Charles Joris, Dominique Catton, Gilles Laubert, Raoul Pastor, Philippe Mentha, and Georges Guerreiro.[4] 
Sylla founded the production company Guiss Guiss Communication in 2003.[1] In 2006, Sylla joined the musical group Bricojardin as its singer.[4] She directed the short film Dakar Deuk Raw in 2008, which examined the ancient tribe of Lesbous in Dakar. 
In 2010, Sylla directed Skirmisher Marc Gueye: My Pen, My Fight, about a veteran of the First Indochina War.[3] She has also performed voice-over work for radio and television.[4] 
She assisted Julien George in the staging of La Puce à l'Oreille in 2012. 
She directed Allons enfants voir si la rose est un cheval vu de dos by Joël Bastard at the Théâtre Am Stram Gram in 2013.[5] Sylla served as co-director of the 2014 film Une simple parole alongside her sister Khady, and finished it when Khady died.[2] The film examines the storytelling tradition in Senegal and received the Diversity Award from the Women's International Film and Television Showcase.[6] Sylla directed Jean et Béatrice by Carole Fréchette at the Théâtre Le Crève-Cœur in 2015. 
The following year, she directed Jean-Luc by Fabrice Melquiot at the Théâtre Am Stram Gram. 
Sylla has taught in conservatories and led theatre workshops.[5] 
Sylla is married to the journalist Modou Mamoune Faye.[1] 
