Selected filmography 
Awards and nominations 
Badamasi: Portrait of a General is a biopic about former Nigerian head of state, Ibrahim Badamasi Babangida (IBB). 
It was directed by Obi Emelonye and stars Enyinna Nwigwe in the lead role as Babangida.[1] It is the first Nollywood political biopic.[2] 
Awards and nominations 
Year Award Category Recipient Result Ref 2020 Africa Movie Academy Awards Best Actor in a Leading Pole Enyinna Nwigwe Nominated [6] Best Visual Effects Badamasi Nominated 2021 Best of Nollywood Awards Best Actor in a Leading Role (English) Enyinna Nwigwe Pending [7] Best Actor in a Supporting Role (English) Sani Danja Pending Movie with the Best Special Effect Badamasi Pending Movie with the Best Production Design Pending Movie with the Best Cinematography Pending 
Badamasi tells the story of Babangida from his origins in the village of Wushishi in Northern Nigeria to his joining the army and time as a Nigerian military head of state. 
It also portrays significant events in Babangida's life including the period of the Nigerian civil war where Babangida sustains injuries I an attempt to rescue a colleague. 
The subsequent military coups and annulment of the June 1993 presidential elections were also portrayed.[1][3] 
Cast 
Production for Badamasi commenced in 2017.[4] The film is set in 1980/1990s Nigeria[4] and was shot on location in Lagos, Minna, Abuja and the University of Nigeria (UNN), Nsukka.[2] The film director told a Pulse Nigeria interviewer that it took him 4 years to convince Babangida to allow him make the biopic. 
The film was initially billed for a 29 November 2019 release date but was delayed due to reported "powerful people" who were against the circulation of the film.[5] There were concerns that the biopic might be an attempt to whitewash Babngida's story as the annulment of the June 1993 presidential elections earned Babangida condemnation.[4] The first look trailer was released in September 2019.[2] Badamasi premiered at the Cineworld O2 Arena in South London on 12 June 2021.[5] 
A reviewer for The Guardian praised the film for its production and attention to technical details noting that "It did not ‘feel’ like Nollywood" and was in keeping with Obi Emelonye's other films including Heart 2 Heart, The Mirror Boy, Last Flight to Abuja and Onye Ozi.[1] 
Devil in Agbada is a 2021 Nigerian action drama film written, produced by Chinneylove Eze and directed by Umanu Elijah.[1] The film stars Erica Nlewedim, Linda Osifo, and Efe Irele.[2] The official poster of the film was unveiled in March 2021.[3][4] The film had its special premiere on 27 June 2021 and had its official theatrical release on 2 July 2021 and opened to mixed reviews from critics but emerged as a success at the box office.[5][6] The film is loosely inspired from the elements of Hollywood.[7] 
Cast 
Linda Osifo as Irene Efe Irele as Okikiola Erica Nlewedim as Tomi Uzor Arukwe as Machado Akin Lewis as Otunba Shonibare Uche Jombo Alexx Ekubo Nosa Rex Etinosa Idemudia Desmond Elliot Alexander Okeke Soso Sobrekan 
Three young women Irene, Okikiola, and Tomi collaborate and team up together to achieve the mission of bringing down Otunda Shonibare,[8] a ruthless politician. The mission involves infiltrating his heavily guarded and impenetrable mansion.[2] 
Eddie Coffie (1959–2015) was a veteran Ghanaian actor, president of the Ghana Actors Guild (GAG) and also a pastor.[1][2][3][4] He featured in many Ghanaian movies like Bob Smith's Diabolo, Dirty Tears Sinking Sands and A Northern Affair. 
Career 
References 
In 1992, Coffie featured in many Ghanaian movies like Bob Smith's Diabolo, which he played the main role as the snake-pastor who turns into a strange creature devouring raw eggs and suffering from Hallucinations.[5][6][7] He went on and featured in several movies including Dirty Tears in 1996 and both Dangerous Game II and The Suspect in 1997.[4] He also featured in the multiple award winning movies Sinking Sands in 2011 and A Northern Affair in 2014.[9] In 2014, he also featured in the Ghanaian-Nigerian movie My Taxi Soul starring alongside Martha Ankomah, Kalsoume Sinare and Eddie Watson.[10] 
Ghana Actors Guild 
In October 2014, Coffie was elected as the president of the Ghana Actors Guild (GAG) after garnering 93 votes out of 166 votes cast.[1][11] He served in that role until his death in 2015.[3][12][13] He was a member of the Ghana Culture Forum Outreach taskforce team with veteran actress and politician Dzifa Gomashie serving as the team leader.[14][13] Through his role as President of GAG, he worked as a key member of the creative arts executives along with GHAMRO president Kojo Antwi and MUSIGHA president Bice Obour to ensure the introduction of Insurance for entertainers in Ghana.[15] 
Filmography 
Diabolo (1992)[1][16][17] Fatal Decision (1993)[8] Who Killed Nancy? (1995)[8] Sarah II (1995)[8] Candidates for Hell (1996)[18][8] Dirty Tears (1996)[8] Dangerous Game II (1997)[8] The Suspect (1997)[8] Burning Desire 2 (2002) Sinking Sands (2011) Burning Desire 3 (2012) Burning Desire 4 (2012) The Power of Buttocks (2013)[19] A Northern Affair (2014)[7] My Taxi Soul (2014)[8] My Taxi Soul 2 (2014) 
Personal life 
Coffie had three children; two sons and a daughter.[20] On 30 October 2015, he died of high blood pressure at the Ridge Hospital.[2][21][22] He was buried on 19 December 2015, with his final funeral rites taking place at the Azumah Nelson Sports Complex, Kaneshie.[20] With his role and contribution to the arts and creative and theatre industry, he was given a state burial by the government of Ghana through the Ministry of Tourism, Culture and Creative Arts contributing to the funeral and representing the government in organizing the funeral through the Substantive Minister, Elizabeth Ofosu-Agyare and her deputy Dzifa Gomashie.[23] 
His funeral was well attended by several musicians and actors including Nii-Odoi Mensah, Rose Mensah (Kyeiwaa), Prince Yawson (Waakye) and Augustine Abbey (Idikoko) Bill Asamoah, Emelia Brobbey, Grace Nortey, Kojo Dadson, Kalsoume Sinare and Barima Sidney.[24] 
Aderonke Adeola is a Nigerian film director, art historian, fashion entrepreneur, script-writer and producer. 
