Christophe Pognon (born 11 October 1977, in Cotonou) is a former tennis player from Benin. 
Pognon represented his native country at the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia, where he was defeated in the first round by Brazil's Gustavo Kuerten. 
The right-hander reached his highest singles ATP-ranking on 27 August 2001, when he became World Number 804. 
Pognon participated in Davis Cup ties for Benin from 1994–2003, posting a 14–17 record in singles and a 1–1 record in doubles. 
Aloÿs Nizigama (born 18 June 1966) is a retired Burundian long-distance runner who specialized in the 5000 and 10,000 metres. 
In his career, Nizigama ran 21 sub-28 minute 10,000 metres races, 2nd only to Haile Gebrselassie with 23 times.[2] 
International competitions 
Thierry Ndikumwenayo (born 26 March 1997)[1] is a Burundian long-distance runner. 
In 2019, he competed in the men's 10,000 metres at the 2019 World Athletics Championships held in Doha, Qatar.[1] He did not finish his race.[1] 
In 2014, he won the silver medal in the boys' 3000 metres event at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics held in Nanjing, China.[2][3] 
In 2017, he competed in the senior men's race at the 2017 IAAF World Cross Country Championships held in Kampala, Uganda.[4] He finished in 95th place.[4] 
In 2019, he competed in the senior men's race at the 2019 IAAF World Cross Country Championships held in Aarhus, Denmark.[5] He finished in 9th place.[5] In 2019, he won the men's race at the Cross Internacional de la Constitución held in Alcobendas, Spain.[6] 
