A leg is a weight-bearing and locomotive anatomical structure, usually having a columnar shape. 
During locomotion, legs function as "extensible struts".[1] The combination of movements at all joints can be modeled as a single, linear element capable of changing length and rotating about an omnidirectional "hip" joint. 
