Destiny's Child reunited for a farewell performance at the 2006 NBA All-Star Game on February 19, 2006, in Houston, Texas; however, Knowles commented, "It's the last album, but it's not the last show."[65][66] Their final televised performance was at the Fashion Rocks benefit concert in New York a few days later.[65] On March 28, 2006, Destiny's Child was inducted into the Hollywood Walk of Fame, the 2,035th recipient of the coveted recognition.[67] At the 2006 BET Awards, Destiny's Child won Best Group, a category they also earned in 2005 and 2001.[68] 
Destiny's Child first charted in November 1997 with "No, No, No", the lead single from their self-titled debut album, which was released in the United States on February 17, 1998, featuring productions by Tim & Bob, Rob Fusari, Jermaine Dupri, Wyclef Jean, Dwayne Wiggins and Corey Rooney.[1] Destiny's Child peaked at number sixty-seven on the Billboard 200 and number fourteen on the Billboard Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums.[18] It managed to sell over one million copies in the United States, earning a platinum certification by the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA).[19] The remix version to "No, No, No", reached number one on the Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles & Tracks and number three on the Billboard Hot 100. 
In 1998, Destiny's Child garnered three Soul Train Lady of Soul awards[8] including Best New Artist for "No, No, No". 
Knowles considered their debut successful but not huge, claiming as a neo soul record it was too mature for the group at the time.[20] 
